lso allow your organization to retain talent. And as we also see, it will allow you to grow faster than the competition. Companies that are the best at training and retraining their people have 65% less staff turnover than other organizations. Because good people tend to be obsessed with self-development. And if their employer provides it, they'll stay longer. We've seen successful examples of this at Skyscanner, Airbnb, also at LinkedIn, or companies like Google or Facebook that spend enormous time on training days on training their individuals The reason they setting them up is because traditional educational institutions just aren fast or adaptive enough to deliver the right type of people And we also see the limitations of online learning Online learning is great as a supplement but the first step is usually offline physical learning These companies have been able to build not only self-driving organizations, but they've built self-learning organizations. Organizations that can learn organically to adapt and to change, starting at the individual level. We call these people people who have a growth mindset. We also call them T-shaped players. They have a wide range of interests and knowledge and some areas where they have a very deep level of knowledge. They can understand and talk other departments or other people's language. For example, marketeers who also understand tech, analytics, behavioral psychology or design. Or data scientists who also understand customer experience, product design, accounting finance and operations. And we believe that you should be training, retaining, but also finding these types of people. They will allow change to spread faster within the organization. Their brains are wired for change. And what's beautiful is for these companies, change actually becomes an advantage rather than a threat. They embrace the change they embrace the speed leaving the others in the dust So how not to implement the first steps of a learning organization From our experience we advise a couple things We actually think you shouldn do the first part alone You need a partner for the first part Why Because these programs tend to be very complex, very expensive, it takes super long to set up, training is an expertise, a core competence that you might not have within your organization. The digital world moves too fast which means a lot of curriculums get out of date in a very short amount of time and teaching needs to be extremely practical, extremely hands-on for people to understand the concepts more rapidly. Let me repeat that, it needs to be extremely practical. So what we advise is to de-risk the first steps of building a learning organization by having a partner. And once you've used a partner to build that first pilot or de-risk that first step, then we will have embedded the learning organization within the DNA of your company. And then you can do it alone. If you're interested in making those first steps of building a self-learning organization, get in touch and we'll show you the step-by-step process. Thank you.",
